li.p:
      The pivot positions are indicated below

	\left[
	\begin{array}{rrrr}
	{\mathbf 2} \amp 4 \amp 6 \amp -1 \\
	-3 \amp {\mathbf 1} \amp 5 \amp 0 \\
	1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \amp {\mathbf 1} \\
	\end{array}
	\right]
	\sim
	\left[
	\begin{array}{rrrr}
	{\mathbf 1} \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp {\mathbf 1} \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp {\mathbf 1} \\
	\end{array}
	\right]\text{.}

A matrix with a pivot position in every row and every column would have the following reduced row echelon form:
\left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Such a matrix must necessarily have the same number of rows and columns, which means it is what we call a square matrix.

      The pivot positions are indicated below

	\left[
	\begin{array}{rrrr}
	{\mathbf 2} \amp 4 \amp 6 \amp -1 \\
	-3 \amp {\mathbf 1} \amp 5 \amp 0 \\
	1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \amp {\mathbf 1} \\
	\end{array}
	\right]
	\sim
	\left[
	\begin{array}{rrrr}
	{\mathbf 1} \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp {\mathbf 1} \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp {\mathbf 1} \\
	\end{array}
	\right]\text{.}

subsection.p:
In the first example, we have the equations
\begin{alignedat}{4} x_1 \amp {}={} \amp 4 \\ x_2 \amp {}={} \amp -1 \\ x_3 \amp {}={} \amp 2 \\ \end{alignedat}
demonstrating the fact that there is a unique solution (x_1,x_2,x_3) = (4,-1,2).
